body:
The use of a private type in a `where` clause in a trait impl currently results in an erroneous (https://github.com/rust-lang/rust/issues/34537#issuecomment-468161091) `private_in_public` warning. It appears that using `#[allow(private_in_public)]` on the `impl` itself has no effect. That is, the following still emits the lint warning:

```rust
#[derive(Clone)]
struct Bar<T> {
    data: T,
}

pub struct Foo<T> {
    data: Bar<T>,
}

const _: () = {
    #[allow(private_in_public)]
    impl<T> Clone for Foo<T> where Bar<T>: Clone {
        fn clone(&self) -> Self {
            Self {
                data: self.data.clone()
            }
        }
    }
};
```

Instead, to silence the warning, the lint has to be applied on the private item, that is:

```rust
#[derive(Clone)]
#[allow(private_in_public)]
struct Bar<T> {
    data: T,
}
```

This is 1) unexpected, and 2) untenable in situations where the `impl` is being code generated (as in my case). Ideally, if the `#[allow(..)]` is applied to _any_ parent of the "private" use site, the lint should be disabled. This would imply that the first code snippet _would not_ warn, and furthermore, that the following would _also_ not warn:

```rust
#[derive(Clone)]
struct Bar<T> {
    data: T,
}

pub struct Foo<T> {
    data: Bar<T>,
}

#[allow(private_in_public)]
const _: () = {
    impl<T> Clone for Foo<T> where Bar<T>: Clone {
        fn clone(&self) -> Self {
            Self {
                data: self.data.clone()
            }
        }
    }
};
```

cc @petrochenkov
